MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}, today we will learn how to re-ignite the S-IVB to place us on a trajectory towards the Moon.

We are currently in Earth orbit with the S-IVB still attached. Most have been set up for this lesson but I recommend referring to the TLI checklists after completing the lesson for the full procedure, this lesson will get you familiar with the main steps of it.
Let's configure the ORDEAL. Set FDAI 1 to ORB RATE.
Then set it to EARTH. The S-IVB is programmed to maintain a prograde attitude, so setting the ORDEAL FDAI 1 to ORB RATE will visualize this on FDAI 1.
Go to ORBITAL view and focus on Earth. Orient the camera so you can see your orbital trajectory.
Then open the Communication/Tools menu, and open the S-IVB Burn Planner tool. Toggle the Communication/Tools menu if it's still visible after opening the tool.
The S-IVB burn planner has a dedicated camera where the view is aligned with your orbital plane.
You can zoom in and out using the mouse wheel (default mapping), and select what to focus on using the tools UI.
Ensure EARTH is selected. From this view, zoom out until see a few colored lines. The blue line represents your current orbit as well as the initial TLI trajectory.
Zoom out a bit more to see more of the planned trajectory. If you zoom out enough you will eventually see an orange trajectory line. This is the Free Return line.
After the TLI burn, the spacecraft will follow the blue line towards the Moon. If you don't fire any engines to change your trajectory, you will come back from the Moon following that orange line.

The UI of the tool will show you at what Perilune you will have when arriving. This is the point you will use to plan the SPS burn named Lunar Orbit Injection (LOI). The Pe target is defined by the mission plan, typically 60 nmi altitude.
The UI will also present you with the time of ignition, as well as a countdown.
Let's take a look at our trajectory around the Moon. Using the tools UI, click on MOON to view your lunar trajectory.
Notice the white line. This is your trajectory once you enter the lunar sphere of influence, meaning the point where the gravity of the Moon is stronger than the gravity of Earth.
After this point, the Moon controls your trajectory, and is indicated by the white line.
The tool has three parameters you can alter. You can use the PLUS and MINUS buttons to alter the value with the number in-between the buttons. You can adjust the modification value as needed.

The first parameter is the Flight Time Factor. The smaller this value is, the shorter the time it will take to get to the Moon. The shorter the time, the more dV is required by the TLI burn as well as the LOI burn.

While still looking at the Moon, try to press the MINUS button on the Time of Flight factor parameter to decrease it by 0.001. You will see that the trajectory is altered, and will modify the arrival Perilune.
Click on BURN POINT to move the camera to the point of ignition.
There are two other parameters you can use to alter your planned trajectory.

The SOI angle of arrival is at what angle you will reach the lunar gravity of influence. This value can be used to control what location you will have relative to the Moon, when arriving it's sphere of influence (SOI).
The Angle of TLI Departure sets the flight path angle the spacecraft will have on ignition.
Let's keep the values as is. To start planning the burn, press EXECUTE.
This will calculate the burn data needed to reach the trajectory, and insert this into the memory a computer called the Launch Vehicle Digital Computer in the S-IVB that will control the burn.
Stop the Digital Event Timer (DET), then set it to count UP, and set the time to 51:00. The DET is used to aid us with a timer during the TLI sequence. We will start it 9 minutes before ignition.
The next step is to run P15 (TLI Initiate/Cutoff Program). Move over to the CMC and insert V37E 15E to run Program 15.
Noun 33 will show you the planned time of TB6. This is the value from the SIVB Burn Planner, and can't be altered.

TB6 means Time Base 6. The Saturn Instrument Unit (IU) controlled the launch vehicle using a set of timebases. Think of them as pre-programmed sequencer phases, when one is complete, the next can be initiated.
Each timebase is responsible for a block of events like engine starts, shutdowns, separations, ullage burns, etc.
Timebase 1 to Timebase 5, or TB1â€“TB5, covered everything from first-stage ignition through orbital insertion and parking orbit operations.
When you requested the TLI burn parameters through the burn planner, TB6 (Timebase 6) was scheduled. TB6 is the timebase that executes the Trans-Lunar Injection (TLI) sequence.
When ground controllers (via the IU) commands TB6 to start, the S-IVB and IU will begin the TLI process. The time you see on N33 marks this event.
Press PRO to proceed from N33.
Noun 14 will now show you the planned dV in ft/s. This is also a value from the SIVB Burn Planner, and can't be altered. Press PRO to continue.
Noun 95 will count down towards the burn. When the countdown reaches 0, the S-IVB is automatically ignited. Unlike Program 40, you do not press need to press PRO to accept the ignition.

It is important to know that Program 15 on the CMC is only monitoring the burn. The burn itself is fully automatic and controlled by a computer in the S-IVB, the Launch Vehicle Digital Computer (LVDC).
The first Event is the start of TB6. This happens at 9 minutes and 38 seconds before ignition (T -09:38).
TB6 has started. This is indicated by the UPLINK ACTY light on the CMC warning light grid, and the S II SEP light on the LV ENGINES indicators.

The next event will be at T -09:00 and is indicated by the S II SEP light extinguishing. At this point, be prepared to start the Digital Event Timer (DET). It will then count up from 51:00, meaning it will reach 00:00 and count up on S-IVB engine ignition. Start it on my MARK.
MARK, S II SEP light is off, start the Digital Event Timer. We are now 9 minutes from TLI ignition.
Use timescale to about two minutes before ignition. At this point, verify that the S-IVB maneuvers to the burn attitude.
Set the XLUNAR switch on panel 2 to INJECT. This is typically done earlier but it is important to know where it is. This needs to be on INJECT to allow the ignition.
At T -01:40, or when DET shows 58:15, the DSKY blanks for 5 seconds.
The S II SEP light will again illuminate at DET 58:36 (T -01:24), and will go out at DET 59:42 (T -00:18).
The LV ENGINE 1 light will illuminate at DET 59:59 (T -00:01), and will go out 2 seconds after ignition (DET 00:02).

Ignition! The engine will now burn and R2 of NOUN 95 will reduce towards 0. The S-IVB will automatically cut off when the burn is complete. It's a rather lengthy burn, but monitor P15 on the CMC, the attitude on FDAI 1, and the LV TANK PRESSURE gauges.

Cut off! If everything went correctly, we should now be on a trajectory towards the Moon! At this point, you do no longer need the S-IVB so go ahead and separate it using the CSM/LV SEP trigger button.
We should now be free from the S-IVB. In this mission, we do not have the Lunar Module with us, so we can skip the T&D maneuver.
Good job, this concludes this lesson.

Title: Lesson 11 - Trans-Lunar Injection
Description: Trans-Lunar Injection is one of the major steps in a lunar mission, and is a burn performed by the S-IVB. The burn happens after ascending into parking orbit. In this lesson, we will learn how to get ourself on a trajectory towards the Moon!
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

In this lesson we will take a look at the S-IVB burn tool used to plan a Trans-Lunar Injection (TLI).

The tool requires you to play around with some parameters to create the desired trajectory that will take you to the Moon. The goal of the trajectory is to do a few things:
1) Get to the Moon
2) Arrive at a desired altitude (Pe)
3) Optionally take you on a free return trajectory, that will take you back to Earth if needed. And if so, return you to a given altitude above the Earth.

Once the trajectory has been planned, the CMC will take care of the burn. Program 15 - TLI INITIATE/CUTOFF is used to ignite the engine, as well as monitor the burn.
